<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">OPENING STATEMENT</TI>
<P>In 1885 the English courts held that positive covenants do not bind successors in title to property in <CASEREF><SOC>Austerberry v. Corporation of Oldham</SOC></CASEREF> (the &ldquo;<EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule&rdquo;).</P>
<P>Since then, courts in both England and Canada have recognized that the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule may create harsh consequences, leaving a party free to enjoy the benefit of a negative covenant without having to perform a corresponding positive covenant.</P>
<P>This is such a case.</P>
<P>Jameson House is a development that involves a number of airspace parcels. The owners of residential strata units in Jameson House use a parkade owned by the Appellant pursuant to a detailed easement agreement which requires them to pay a share of the cost of maintaining and operating the parkade. The residential strata owners continue to use the parkade, but do not want to be bound to pay a share of the cost of maintaining and operating it. The Respondent has obtained a declaration that it is not bound by the easement agreement.</P>
<P>The English courts have identified two common law principles that modify the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule, the conditional grant principle and the benefit and burden principle.</P>
<P>In <CASEREF><SOC>Parkinson v. Reid</SOC></CASEREF>, the Supreme Court of Canada recognized the existence of the benefit and burden principle, but that decision seems to have been ignored or forgotten.</P>
<P>The Ontario Court of Appeal is the only appellate court in Canada that has recently and expressly considered the common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule. It recognized the conditional grant principle, but not the benefit and burden principal.</P>
<P>It is time for B.C. to recognize the common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule, which, if applied in this case, would require the Respondent to comply with the easement agreement.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART 1&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>a)</N><TI>Findings of Fact Are Accepted</TI>
<P>1. The Appellant refers to and accepts the facts referred to in the Reasons for Judgment in paragraphs 1&ndash;5 and 26&ndash;50.
<P1>Reasons for Judgment, para. 1&ndash;5 and 26&ndash;50, A.R., p. 28&ndash;33</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>b)</N><TI>The Jameson House Development</TI>
<P>2. Jameson House is a 37-story office, retail and residential mixed-use concrete high-rise tower.
<P1>Reasons for Judgment, para 28</P1></P>
<P>3. Jameson House is constructed on a single lot. Jameson House is comprised of five airspace parcels and a remainder parcel:
