<P1>Reasons for Judgment, para 28&ndash;31</P1></P>
<P>4. The parkade at Jameson House is unique, as it is an automated parking and storage system (the &ldquo;Parkade&rdquo;). A vehicle is driven into an elevator, at which point the driver and passengers disembark and an automated system parks the vehicle in the Parkade. The cost of operating and maintaining the Parkade is substantial.
<P1>Reasons for Judgment, para 32</P1></P>
<P>5. The Owners, Strata Plan BCS 4006 (the &ldquo;Strata Corporation&rdquo;) own Airspace Parcel # 1. The Appellant owns the Remainder Parcel, which is where the Parkade is located and pays the costs of maintaining and operating the Parkade. The Appellant then seeks reimbursement from the other owners and occupants of Jameson House pursuant to an easement agreement.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>c)</N><TI>The Easement Agreement</TI>
<P>6. The design of Jameson House requires the owners and occupants of each airspace parcel to be able to use and access the shared facilities such as the electrical, mechanical and fire suppression systems, as well as the Parkade.
<P1>Reasons for Judgment, para 33</P1></P>
<P>7. On October 1, 2010, a comprehensive easement agreement was executed to ensure that the owners and occupants of each airspace parcel are able to use and access portions of Jameson House they do not own and use and enjoy the shared mechanical, electrical and fire suppression systems and Parkade the (&ldquo;Easement Agreement&rdquo;). The Easement Agreement requires the owners and occupants of Jameson House to pay a share of the cost of operating and maintaining the Shared Facilities.
<P1>Reasons for Judgment, para 34</P1></P>
<P>8. In particular, the Easement Agreement permits the owners of residential strata units (the &ldquo;Residential Strata Owners&rdquo;) to use the Parkade and requires the Strata Corporation to pay a share of the cost of maintaining and operating the Parkade (the &ldquo;Parkade Expenses&rdquo;).</P>
<P>9. The key portions of the Easement Agreement include: :
<P1>(a) clause 5.3 which grants an easement permitting the Residential Strata Owners to use the Parkade;</P1>
<P1>(b) clauses 5.3.6 to 5.3.10 which specify the Parkade Expenses to which the Residential Strata Owners are required to contribute and set out the manner by which the costs are to be calculated, charged to the Strata Corporation, paid and disputed;</P1>
<P1>(c) clauses 5.4 and 5.9 which provide similar rights of access to the owners of other airspace parcels and require the owners of those airspace parcels to pay a share of the Parkade Expenses; and</P1>
<P1>(d) clause 13.1 which provides that the Easement Agreement runs with the land and is binding on successors.
<P2>Appeal Book, Vol 1, pp. 128, 151&ndash;154, 154-155, 156-157 and 175</P2></P1></P>
<P>10. The Easement Agreement was registered in the Land Title Office on December 24, 2010, and the terms of the Easement Agreement were disclosed to potential purchasers in disclosure statements filed with the Financial Institutions Commission. Until shortly before the hearing of this matter, the strata by-laws stated that the Strata Corporation was bound by the Easement Agreement.
<P1>Reasons for Judgment, para 49</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>d)</N><TI>Payment of Parkade Expenses</TI>
<P>11. The Residential Strata Owners have used the Parkade continuously since the building has been occupied. There is no evidence that the Residential Strata Owners intend to disclaim their right to use the Parkade.</P>
<P>12. The Strata Corporation paid the Parkade Expenses from August 1, 2011 until about May, 2016.
<P1>Reasons for Judgment, para 50</P1></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART 2&mdash;ERRORS IN JUDGMENT</TI>
<P>13. The trial judge erred by:
<P1>(a) concluding that the decision of the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Heritage Capital Corp. v. Equitable Trust Co.</SOC><CITE>2016 SCC 19</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <EM>(&ldquo;Heritage Capital&rdquo;)</EM> is authority for the proposition that the only circumstance in which a positive covenant will be binding on successors in title is when a statute provides for the covenant to run with the land;</P1>
<P1>(b) concluding that the provisions of the Easement Agreement which require the Strata Corporation to pay a share of the Parkade Expenses were not enforceable because the obligation to pay a share of the Parkade Expenses is a positive covenant that does not run with the land, which conclusion was based on the erroneous premise that the rule in <EM>Austerberry</EM> is an absolute rule that has not been modified and does not permit exceptions;</P1>
<P1>(c) not recognizing and applying the conditional grant principle which has been accepted by both the English courts and the Ontario courts and the benefit and burden principle which has been accepted by the English courts; and</P1>
<P1>(d) failing to consider the surrounding circumstances in which the Easement Agreement was made and the objective intentions and commercial purposes of the Easement Agreement at the time it was made in determining that the Strata Corporation's right to use the Parkade was not conditional on the payment of the Parkade Expenses.</P1></P>
<P>14. The Appellant accepts that the trial judge was bound to follow other decisions of the B.C. Supreme Court which misapplied the decision in <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> and did not recognize and apply the conditional grant principle and the benefit and burden principle.</P>
<P>15. The Court of Appeal should accept that the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule is not absolute and has been modified to incorporate the conditional grant principle and the benefit and burden principle. The Court of Appeal should find that the Strata Corporation must pay the Parkade Expenses required by the Easement Agreement pursuant to the conditional grant principle or the benefit and burden principle.</P>
<P>16. Accordingly, this factum will not focus on the errors of the trial judge (as she was bound by the previous decisions of the B.C. Supreme Court), but rather on the reasons the Court of Appeal should accept and apply the conditional grant principle and benefit and burden principle, either as a case of first impression, or as an incremental modification of the common law.</P>
<P>17. This factum will address:
<P1>(a) the meaning of the decision in <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> and the misapplication of the <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> decision by courts in Ontario and B.C.;</P1>
<P1>(b) the historical development of modifications to the rule in <EM>Austerberry</EM> in Canada and England and the current state of the law; and</P1>
<P1>(c) the application of the conditional grant principle and the benefit and burden principle to the facts in this case, in respect of which the Appellant submits the trial judge did make an error of law by failing to properly construe the Easement Agreement.</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART 3&mdash;ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>Standard of Review</TI>
<P>18. Each of the errors identified in paragraph 13 are errors of law, as the trial judge misapplied <EM>Heritage Capital</EM>, failed to recognize the existence of a legal principle (the conditional grant principle and the benefit and burden principle) and approached the interpretation of the Easement Agreement without considering any of the surrounding circumstances that existed when the Easement Agreement was made.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>Introduction&mdash;The <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule</TI>
<P>19. In <CASEREF><SOC>Austerberry v. Corporation of Oldham</SOC></CASEREF>, the English courts decided that, at common law, positive covenants do not run with the land since a party cannot be liable to perform an obligation under a contract to which they are not a party (the &ldquo;<EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule&rdquo;).
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Austerberry v. Corporation of Oldham</SOC><YEAR>1885</YEAR><CITE>29 Ch. D. 750</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>20. English law has evolved since 1885. In England, the courts have recognized two common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule:
<P1>(a) the conditional grant principle, in which a positive covenant is enforceable against a successor in title if the grant of easement is conditional on the performance of the positive covenant; and</P1>
<P1>(b) the benefit and burden principle, in which a positive covenant is enforceable on a successor in title when the benefit of the easement and the burden of the positive covenant are conferred in the same agreement and the enjoyment of the benefit is relevant to the imposition of the burden. The benefit and burden principle permits the beneficiary of an easement to avoid the burden of performing a positive covenant by disclaiming the benefit of the easement.</P1></P>
<P>21. The Supreme Court of Canada considered and accepted the benefit and burden principle in <CASEREF><SOC>Parkinson v. Reid</SOC></CASEREF>, but decided that the principle did not apply to the facts before the court.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Parkinson v. Reid</SOC><CITE>[1966] S.C.R. 162</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Parkinson&rdquo;)</EM></P1></P>
<P>22. Two Ontario Court of Appeal decisions have accepted that the conditional grant principle applies in Ontario, but neither decision accepted or applied the benefit and burden principle.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Amberwood Investments Ltd. v. Durham Condominium Corp. No. 123</SOC><YEAR>2002</YEAR><CITE>58 O.R. (3d) 481</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Amberwood</EM>&rdquo;)</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Black v. Owen</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 397</CITE></CASEREF> <EM>(&ldquo;Black&rdquo;)</EM></P1></P>
<P>23. In <EM>Amberwood</EM>, the Ontario Court of Appeal declined to accept the benefit and burden principle out of deference to the legislature and a concern that the English law was unsettled. In <EM>Black</EM>, the Ontario Court of Appeal was not asked to overturn <EM>Amberwood</EM>, nor was the five-judge panel required to overturn a previous decision requested.</P>
<P>24. Until recently the B.C. courts had not expressly considered the common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule. Three recent decisions of the B.C. Supreme Court (including the decision on appeal) have held that there are no common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule in B.C.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Strata Plan LMS 3905 v. Crystal Square Parking Corp.</SOC><CITE>2017 BCSC 71</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Crystal Square</EM>&rdquo;)</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>The Owners Strata Plan NWS 3457 v. The Owners Strata Plan LMS 1425</SOC><CITE>2017 BCSC 1346</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Scottsdale</EM>&rdquo;)</P1></P>
<P>25. The B.C. Court of Appeal has never expressly considered the common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule.</P>
<P>26. The decision in <EM>Scottsdale</EM> emphasized the need for a definitive ruling from the B.C. Court of Appeal:
<QUOTE><P>I am advised that the <EM>Crystal Square</EM> decision is under appeal, so perhaps we will receive some clarity from our own Court of Appeal whether they are prepared to adopt the <EM>Amberwood</EM> exception into B.C. law. (para 50)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>27. Likewise, the trial judge commented:
<QUOTE><P>Though the Ontario Court of Appeal has recently re-affirmed that a conditional grant in line with the description from <EM>Halsbury's</EM> is enforceable in that province, two decisions from the British Columbia Supreme Court have recently concluded otherwise. I note that <EM>Crystal Square</EM> is currently under appeal, so our Court of Appeal may reach its own decision on that matter. (para 155)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>28. More and more people in B.C. live in developments in which common facilities are shared. The B.C. Court of Appeal should recognize both of the common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule to ensure that those who have obtained an easement to use a shared facility contribute to the cost of that facility.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI>The Heritage Capital Decision is Not Dispositive and Has Been Misapplied</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>a)</N><TI>Introduction</TI>
<P>29. The trial judge erred in finding that the decision in <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> stood for the proposition that the only exceptions to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule arise from statute. Indeed, a number of other decisions have made the same error. <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> was a decision in which a statutory exception was at issue. Common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule were neither argued, nor considered. The Supreme Court of Canada did not have to grapple with, and did not overrule, its decision in <EM>Parkinson</EM> in which it recognized the benefit and burden principle.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>b)</N><TI>Heritage Capital Did Not Address Common Law Modifications</TI>
<P>30. The decision of the Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> is not authority for the proposition that the only circumstance in which an affirmative covenant will be binding on successors in title is where a statute provides for it, merely because it contains the following statement:
<QUOTE><P>The idea of a payment obligation running with land is by its nature unusual. In fact, it is undisputed that at common law, positive covenants cannot run with the land (<CASEREF><SOC>Austerberry v. Oldham</SOC><YEAR>1885</YEAR><CITE>29 Ch. D. 750</CITE><COURTJUR>Eng. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>). This rule is founded on the principle that at common law, a person cannot be made liable upon a contract unless he or she was party to it (<CASEREF><SOC>Rhone v. Stephens</SOC><CITE>[1994] 2 A.C. 310</CITE><COURTJUR>U.K. H.L.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>). The rule against positive covenants running with the land applies even if an agreement contains an express intention to the contrary (<CASEREF><SOC>Amberwood Investments Ltd. v. Durham Condominium Corp. No. 123</SOC><YEAR>2002</YEAR><CITE>58 O.R. (3d) 481</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>). As a result, the common law rule is that <UNDER>&ldquo;[n]o personal or affirmative covenant, requiring the expenditure of money or the doing of some act, can, apart from statute, be made to run with the land&rdquo;</UNDER> (V. Di Castri, <EM>Registration of Title to Land (loose-leaf)</EM>, vol. 1, at p. 10&ndash;4 (emphasis added), quoted in <CASEREF><SOC>Westbank Holdings Ltd. v. Westgate Shopping Centre Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2001 BCCA 268</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>155 B.C.A.C. 1</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>B.C.C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at para. 16). The issue in the instant case is whether and to what extent s. 29 of the <EM>HRA</EM> displaces the common law rule by permitting positive covenants to run with the land. (para 25)</P>
<P>(Emphasis added)</P>
<P>(the &ldquo;Heritage Capital Statement&rdquo;)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>31. The issue in <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> was whether, and to what extent, a provision in the <EM>Historical Resources Act</EM> modified the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule by permitting positive covenants to run with the land.</P>
<P>32. There was no consideration of any common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule because the only issue before the court was the application of a statutory exception. The Heritage Capital Statement is limited in application to cases involving statutory exceptions to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>c)</N><TI>The Heritage Capital Statement is Inconsistent With The Authorities</TI>
<P>33. The Heritage Capital Statement cannot have been meant as an absolute rule because the authorities referred to as justification for the proposition that a positive covenant cannot run with the land apart from statute are contrary to that proposition.</P>
<P>34. The Heritage Capital Statement must apply only to cases where a statutory exception is engaged because:
<P1>(a) two of the cases referred to in the Heritage Capital Statement recognized that the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule had been modified to permit common law exceptions. <EM>Amberwood</EM> recognized that the conditional grant principle might permit a positive covenant to run with the land. <CASEREF><SOC>Rhone v. Stephens</SOC></CASEREF> recognized that the benefit and burden principle might permit a positive covenant to run with the land; and
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Rhone v. Stephens</SOC><CITE>[1994] 2 A.C. 310</CITE><COURTJUR>U.K. H.L.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Rhone</EM>&rdquo;)</P2></P1>
<P1>(b) none of the cases referred to in the Heritage Capital Statement expressly disclaim the possibility of common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule.</P1></P>
<P>35. The only case referred to in the Heritage Capital Statement that does not recognize common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule is <EM>Westbank</EM> (&ldquo;<EM>Westbank</EM>&rdquo;), in which the B.C. Court of Appeal quotes an extract from <EM>DiCastri, Registration of Title to Land</EM> that includes the proposition that a positive covenant cannot run with the land apart from statute.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Westbank Holdings Ltd. v. Westgate Shopping Centres Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2001 BCCA 268</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Westbank</EM>&rdquo;)</P1>
<P1>V. Di Castri, <EM>Registration of Title to Land (loose-leaf)</EM>, vol. 1, at p. 10&ndash;4</P1></P>
<P>36. The decision in <EM>Westbank</EM> and the reference to the <EM>Di Castri</EM> text in the <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> Statement are of limited value because:
<P1>(a) the Court of Appeal was not asked to consider the existence or application of the conditional grant principle or benefit and burden principle in <EM>Westbank</EM>, nor did it consider the decision in <EM>Parkinson</EM>;</P1>
<P1>(b) the <EM>Di Castri</EM> text referred to in <EM>Westbank</EM> was published in 1987, years before the decisions in <EM>Rhone</EM> and <EM>Amberwood</EM> confirmed the common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule;</P1>
<P1>(c) the authorities <EM>Di Castri</EM> cites as authority for the proposition that the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule is absolute apart from statutory exceptions do not support that proposition; and</P1>
<P1>(d) <EM>Westbank</EM> was decided prior to the decision in <EM>Amberwood</EM> which confirmed the conditional grant principle was part of Ontario law and before a number of English decisions which applied the common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>d)</N><TI>Heritage Capital Did Not Address the Decision in <EM>Parkinson</EM></TI>
<P>37. In <EM>Parkinson</EM>, the Supreme Court of Canada recognized that the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule was not absolute and had been modified by the benefit and burden principle. If the Supreme Court of Canada intended <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> to overrule <EM>Parkinson</EM> it had to do so expressly.</P>
<P>38. In <EM>Parkinson</EM>, the Supreme Court of Canada recognized the benefit and burden principle expressed in <CASEREF><SOC>Halsall v. Brizell</SOC></CASEREF>, the case from which the benefit and burden principle originated, but concluded that it did not apply to the facts in <EM>Parkinson</EM>.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Halsall v. Brizell</SOC><CITE>[1957] Ch. 169</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Halsall&rdquo;)</EM></P1></P>
<P>39. <EM>Parkinson</EM> involved an obligation to repair a stairway that had been damaged in a fire. The issue was whether a positive covenant to repair a stairway ran with the land to bind successors in title. The original parties had agreed that a neighbour could use a wall as a party-wall so long as he agreed to keep the stairway in good repair.</P>
<P>40. The judgment of the Ontario Court of Appeal was delivered by Kelly JA and he relied on the English decision in <EM>Halsall</EM>. In <EM>Halsall</EM> a predecessor in title had been granted the right to use the estate roads and sewers and had covenanted to pay a portion of those cost of maintaining these facilities. It was held that a party could not exercise their rights without paying the costs necessary to ensure that they could be exercised. Kelly JA wrote:
<QUOTE><P>...[In <CASEREF><SOC>Halsall v. Brizell</SOC></CASEREF>] [t]he Court held that <EM>prima facie</EM> the covenants contained in the deed were unenforceable in that a positive covenant in the terms contained in the deed did not run with the land. But the Court further held that the defendants were not entitled to take advantage of the trusts granting them the use of the road and other benefits created without undertaking the obligations which were attached thereto. The defendants were free to abandon the use of the roads and remain free from the onus of repairing, but if they chose to avail themselves of the use of the roads, they must assume the burden of repairing.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Parkinson v. Reid</SOC><CITE>[1965] 1 O.R. 117</CITE><COURTJUR>ONCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> para 13</P1></P>
<P>41. Kelly JA described three grounds on which the plaintiff was entitled to succeed, the third of which concerned the principle from <EM>Halsall</EM>.</P>
<P>42. In the decision of the Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Parkinson</EM>, Cartwright J. wrote for the court and summarized the conclusions of the Court of Appeal:
<QUOTE><P>The reasons for judgment of the Court of Appeal were delivered by Kelly J.A. After reciting the facts he held, (i) that there was no privity of contract between the plaintiff and the defendants, (ii) that there was no privity of estate between them and, (iii) that the covenant to repair and reconstruct the stairway did not run with the land. I agree with the views of the learned Justice of Appeal on these three points...</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>However, Kelly J.A. went on to hold the plaintiff entitled to succeed on three grounds. (para 11)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>43. Cartwright J. dealt with the benefit and burden principle (the third ground) as follows:
<QUOTE><P>The third ground was based on the maxim, <EM>Qui sentit commodum sentire debet et onus</EM>. It was said that as the appellants' predecessor in title, Telford Sinclair Parkinson, and the appellants themselves, had enjoyed the privileges contained in the agreements registered as numbers 5294, 5330, 6134, and 6518 referred to in the deed dated April 1, 1946, in part recited above, they could not refuse to perform the obligations contained in the agreement 12360. The first four mentioned agreements were not put in evidence but counsel for the appellants, for the purposes of this appeal, was willing to admit that they conferred on the owners of lot 28 the right to use the westerly wall on lot 29 as a party-wall.</P>
<P>Assuming that so long as the appellants made use of the last-mentioned wall as a party-wall they were bound to keep the stairway in repair, they ceased to be under any such obligation when they no longer made use of the respondent's wall. It is not suggested that the appellants have made any use of that wall since their building was destroyed by fire. A case in which this principle was applied is <CASEREF><SOC>Halsall v. Brizell</SOC></CASEREF> which was discussed in the reasons of Kelly J.A.</P>
<P>For the above reasons I am of opinion that since the time when the building on lot 28 was destroyed the appellants have been under no obligation enforceable at law or in equity to replace the stairway. (para 17&ndash;19)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>44. The Supreme Court of Canada clearly recognized the existence of the benefit and burden principle&mdash;it referred to <EM>Halsall</EM>, the leading English decision and considered the benefit and burden principle, deciding that it did not apply because the appellants had disclaimed and no longer received the benefit of the agreement.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>e)</N><TI>Heritage Capital Did Not Overrule Parkinson</TI>
<P>45. In <EM>Parkinson</EM>, the Supreme Court of Canada recognized that the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule had been modified by the benefit and burden principle.</P>
<P>46. Even if recognition of the benefit and burden principle in <EM>Parkinson</EM> was only <EM>obiter dicta</EM>, it was part of the &ldquo;wider circle of analysis which was obviously intended for guidance and which should be accepted as authoritative&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Henry</SOC><CITE>2005 SCC 76</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>47. <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> cannot have the effect of overruling that part of the decision in <EM>Parkinson</EM> which dealt with the benefit and burden principle because to overrule its own decisions, the Supreme Court of Canada &ldquo;must be satisfied based on compelling reasons that the precedent was wrongly decided and should be overruled&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Teva Canada Ltd. vs. TD Canada Trust</SOC><CITE>2017 SCC 51</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>48. Since the court in <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> did not mention <EM>Parkinson</EM> it cannot be taken to have overruled it. Since it did not do so, <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> must be reconciled with <EM>Parkinson</EM> by acknowledging that the <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> Statement is limited to matters involving a statutory exception to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule and that <EM>Parkinson</EM> remains a binding precedent.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>f)</N><TI>The Misapplication of Heritage Capital</TI>
<P>49. Four Canadian decisions (including the decision on appeal) have misapplied the decision in <EM>Heritage</EM> Capital by stating that <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> is authority for the proposition that the only circumstance in which an affirmative covenant will be binding on successors in title is where a statute provides for an exception.
<P1><EM>Jameson House</EM>, para 59</P1>
<P1><EM>Black</EM>, paragraph 41</P1>
<P1><EM>Crystal Square</EM>, paragraph 45 and 55</P1>
<P1><EM>Scottsdale</EM>, paragraph 43</P1></P>
<P>50. The repeated misapplication of the <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> decision has reinforced the erroneous notion that Canadian law does not recognize any modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule other than statutory exceptions, which is inconsistent with the decisions in <EM>Parkinson, Amberwood</EM> and <EM>Black</EM>, all of which recognized a modification to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule.</P>
<P>51. That inconsistency is highlighted in the decision of the Ontario Court of Appeal in <EM>Black</EM> which both expressly recognized the validity of the conditional grant principle <UNDER>and</UNDER> held that <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> prohibited positive covenants from binding successors in title &ldquo;apart from statute&rdquo;.
<P1><EM>Black</EM>, paragraph 40 and 63</P1></P>
<P>52. Simply put, the <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> Statement cannot be authority for absolute adherence to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule apart from statutory exceptions when that proposition is inconsistent with the decisions in <EM>Amberwood</EM> and <EM>Rhone</EM> (which the Supreme Court of Canada referred to as the basis for the Heritage Capital Statement) and the decision of the Ontario Court of Appeal in <EM>Black</EM> which accepts the Heritage Capital Statement as binding authority, then re-affirms the validity of the conditional grant principle, which is precisely the type of common law exception to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule that would seem to be precluded by the Heritage Capital Statement.</P>
<P>53. The only way to reconcile these decisions is to accept that <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> applies only to cases in which a statutory exception is at issue.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>D.</N><TI>The Austerberry Rule Is Not Absolute</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>a)</N><TI>Introduction</TI>
<P>54. The trial judge erred by concluding that the obligation to pay for the Parkade Expenses pursuant to the Easement Agreement was not enforceable because it was a positive covenant that does not run with the land. This conclusion is premised on the erroneous finding that the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule is an absolute rule that does not admit of exceptions. Common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule have been, or should be, recognized.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>b)</N><TI>Opportunity to Acknowledge Modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule</TI>
<P>55. The <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule is a creature of English common law. If the courts could proscribe that positive covenants run with the land in the first place, then it is rational for the courts to subsequently curtail that proscription by later introducing exceptions and limitations, just as they have done in England where the recognition of such exceptions is now viewed as &ldquo;settled law&rdquo;.</P>
<P>56. According to Professor Ziff, the courts should not view common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule with &ldquo;dismay&rdquo;:
<QUOTE><P>Few would quarrel with the value of wholesale rationalization of the law of servitudes. Until that happens, incremental adjustments through the caselaw should not be regarded with surprise or dismay. There are no compelling reasons why the schemes sought in <EM>Reed Services</EM> and <EM>Tito</EM> should not be regarded as permissible as an ordinary incident of private property ownership. In both cases, allowing affirmative burdens to run with land would have enabled the parties to meet their intended objectives in a straightforward and inexpensive fashion.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Ziff, &ldquo;Positive Covenants Running With the Land: A Castaway on Ocean Land?&rdquo;</EM> Alberta Law Review Vol. XXVII, No. 3, p. 354, para 372</P1></P>
<P>57. Likewise, in his dissent in <EM>Amberwood</EM>, Macpherson J.A. stated:
<QUOTE><P>Canadian society and the patterns of property ownership in 2002 are very different from English society and land ownership in 1885 when Austerberry was decided. The Ontario legislature has recognized the differences and enacted laws mitigating the rigours of the rule in Austerberry&mdash;on 12 occasions.</P>
<P>In my view, the benefit-burden and conditional grant exceptions to the rule in Austerberry can perform a similar role if introduced into the common law of Ontario. As I have tried to explain the exceptions, their adoption would, as required by Bastarache J. in <EM>Friedmann Equity</EM>, result in incremental change with consequences capable of assessment. They would also meet Justice Cardozo's important objective of mitigating hardships or wrongs in appropriate cases. This is one of those cases. The intentions of the original contracting parties and the wording in the agreement they signed are both crystal clear: a regime of reciprocal easements and other benefits and cost sharing was established. Amberwood, a successor in title to one of the contracting parties, chose, with full knowledge of the clear terms of the original agreement, to accept and utilize the benefits of the agreement. In my view, it would be unjust to permit Amberwood to ignore the reciprocal burdens which the agreement so clearly imposes on it. (para. 159-160)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>58. This appeal presents a landmark opportunity for the Court of Appeal to revisit the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule and to recognize that the conditional grant principle and benefit and burden principle have modified the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule, either as a case of first impression or an incremental change to the common law.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>c)</N><TI>The History of Modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule</TI>
<P>59. The <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule was developed in 1885. Since then:
<P1>(a) In 1957, the English High Court established the benefit and burden principle in <EM>Halsall</EM>;</P1>
<P1>(b) In 1966, the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule was first applied in Canada by the Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Parkinson</EM>, ironically in the very case in which the Supreme Court of Canada referred to and considered the benefit and burden principle arising from <EM>Halsall</EM>;</P1>
<P1>(c) In 1977, <CASEREF><SOC>Tito v. Waddell (No. 2)</SOC></CASEREF> expanded the benefit and burden principle;
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Tito v. Waddell (No. 2)</SOC><CITE>[1977] 3 ALL E.R. 129</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Tito&rdquo;)</EM></P2></P1>
<P1>(d) In 1994, the House of Lords rejected the decision in <EM>Tito</EM>, but confirmed the validity of the benefit and burden principle in <EM>Rhone;</EM></P1>
<P1>(e) In 2002, the decision of the Ontario Court of Appeal in <EM>Amberwood</EM> was the first opportunity for a Canadian court to consider whether the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule is absolute, or whether it admits of exceptions.</P1>
<P1>(f) In <EM>Amberwood</EM>, after reviewing the then English law that had modified the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule, the court recognized the conditional grant principle and concluded:
<ITEM><P>It &ldquo;would be inadvisable to adopt the doctrine in <CASEREF><SOC>Halsall v. Brizell</SOC></CASEREF> into Ontario law &ldquo;having regard to the uncertainties and the many frailties in existing common law in England&rdquo;. (Para 75).</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>A free standing conditional grant exception &ldquo;must fail, essentially for the same reason that I have rejected the first exception&rdquo;. (Para 85 - 86).</P></ITEM></P1>
<P1>(g) In 2009, the benefit and burden principle was considered by the court in <CASEREF><SOC>Odd Guys Holdings Ltd. v. C.Y. Ciao Enterprises Co. Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF> with specific reference to the decisions in <EM>Parkinson</EM> and <EM>Halsall</EM>, but the court concluded that it would not apply because there was no benefit.
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Odd Guys Holdings Ltd. v. C.Y. Ciao Enterprises Co. Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2009 BCSC 1867</CITE></CASEREF></P2></P1>
<P1>(h) Since <EM>Amberwood</EM> was decided in 2001, the law in England relating to the benefit and burden exception has gone from what Charron JA described in <EM>Amberwood</EM> as being subject to &ldquo;uncertainties&rdquo; and &ldquo;frailties&rdquo; to being described by <EM>Gale on Easements</EM> (19<SUP>th</SUP> Ed.) as &ldquo;settled&rdquo; law.
<P2>Jonathan Gaunt, Q.C. &amp; The Hon. Mr. Justice Morgan, <EM>Gale on Easements</EM>, 19<SUP>th</SUP> ed. (Sweet &amp; Maxwell: London, 2012), at p. 57</P2></P1>
<P1>(i) There are three decisions of the English Court of Appeal decided since Amberwood that have contributed to the settling of the law;
<ITEM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Davies v. Jones</SOC><CITE>[2009] EWCA Civ 1164</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Davies&rdquo;)</EM>.</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Wilkinson v. Kerdene Limited</SOC><CITE>[2013] EWCA Civ 44</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Wilkinson</EM>&rdquo;).</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Goodman v. Elwood</SOC><CITE>[2013] EWCA Civ 1103</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Goodman</EM>&rdquo;<EM>)</EM>.</P></ITEM></P1>
<P1>(j) The most recent consideration of this issue by an appellate court in Canada was by the Ontario Court of Appeal in <EM>Black</EM>, which declined to address modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule, (although it confirmed the existence of the conditional grant principle). The court, sitting as a three justice division, concluded that the decision in <EM>Amberwood</EM> was binding absent:
<ITEM><P>Being reconsidered by a five justice division, which had not been requested, or</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>An authoritative pronouncement by the Supreme Court of Canada that displaces the majority's holdings in <EM>Amberwood</EM>.</P></ITEM></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>d)</N><TI>The Decision in Amberwood</TI>
<P>60. In Amberwood, the court recognized that the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule created harsh results and should be modified:
<QUOTE><P>It appears to be equally undisputed that the rule at times causes inconvenience, that its application in some cases may even result in unfairness, and that the present state of the law should be modified to meet the needs of modern conveyancing. (para 17)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>61. Charron J. (as she then was) framed her legal analysis as follows:
<QUOTE><P>Therefore, since positive covenants do not run with the land <EM>Amberwood</EM> is not bound by the positive covenant to pay the interim expenses under the Reciprocal Agreement solely by virtue of having acquired the Phase 2 lands with notice of its terms. The question remains whether <EM>Amberwood</EM> is liable to pay the expenses under some other recognized legal principle.</P>
<P>First, DCC 123 places reliance on the doctrine of benefit and burden in <CASEREF><SOC>Halsall v. Brizell</SOC></CASEREF> as a method of avoiding the application of the rule...</P>
<P>The second method relied upon by DCC 123 is the conditional grant of easement. (para. 18&ndash;20)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>62. In <EM>Amberwood</EM>, the Ontario Court of Appeal did not decide that the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule precluded consideration of other legal principles, apart from statutory exceptions, under which <EM>Amberwood</EM> could be liable. It is clear that Charron JA considered the issue in two steps; first, she acknowledged and articulated the general rule that positive covenants do not run with the land, second she considered whether, notwithstanding the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule, there might be another legal principle by which <EM>Amberwood</EM> could be liable.</P>
<P>63. In fact, consistent with this two step approach, Charron JA organized her judgment into and considered separately &ldquo;Statutory exceptions to the rule&rdquo; and &ldquo;Non-statutory methods to circumvent the rule&rdquo; (paragraphs 51 and 53).</P>
<P>64. Charron JA rejected the introduction into Ontario of the benefit and burden principle and the notion of an exception to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule based on a conditional grant. Notwithstanding that conclusion, she wrote:
<QUOTE><P>I note at the outset that the principle from <EM>Halsbury's Laws of England</EM> relied upon by the applications judge seems to me to be consonant with the rule in <EM>Austerberry</EM>. I repeat it here for convenience:
<QUOTE><P>If the facts establish that the granting of a benefit or easement was conditional on assuming the positive obligation, then the obligation is binding. Where the obligation is framed so as to constitute a continuing obligation upon which the grant of the easement was conditional, <EM>the obligation can be imposed as an incident of the easement itself, and not merely a liability purporting to run with the land</EM>. [Emphasis added.]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>Hence, as a matter of construction of the creating instrument itself, if a grant of benefit or easement is framed as conditional upon the continuing performance of a positive obligation, the positive obligation may well be enforceable, not because it would run with the land, but because the condition would serve to limit the scope of the grant itself. In effect, the law would simply be giving effect to the grant. Indeed, as discussed earlier in this judgment at paragraphs 30 and 31, much the same reasoning underlies the law of restrictive covenants. (para 85 - 86)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>65. <EM>Amberwood</EM> does not stand for the proposition that the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule is absolute and exists without modification apart from statute. To the contrary, <EM>Amberwood</EM> recognized that a positive covenant may be enforceable against a successor in title if the performance of the positive covenant is a condition of the grant.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>e)</N><TI>Development of the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule in England</TI>
<P>66. In <EM>Amberwood</EM>, the Ontario Court of Appeal was reluctant to accept and apply the benefit and burden principle because English law was uncertain:
<QUOTE><P>...having regard to the uncertainties and the many frailties of the existing common law in England in this area of the law, it would be inadvisable to adopt these principles in Ontario. (para 75)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>67. Since the Ontario Court of Appeal was concerned with, in part, the frailties and uncertainties in English law, it is logical to consider the approach taken by the English courts since <EM>Amberwood</EM>.</P>
<P>68. Since <EM>Rhone</EM>, English law was moved away from the &ldquo;pure principle of benefit and burden&rdquo; (which required no link between the benefit and burden), but it has emphatically accepted and applied both a conditional grant exception and the benefit and burden exception.</P>
<P>69. In 2013, the Court of Appeal of England and Wales confirmed that the benefit and burden exception was part of English law in <EM>Wilkinson</EM>.</P>
<P>70. In <EM>Wilkinson</EM>, the owners of units in a subdivision attempted to avoid their obligation to pay the cost of operating and repairing common amenities on the basis of the rule in <EM>Austerberry</EM>. The Court of Appeal reconciled the previous English decisions stating:
<QUOTE><P>What Lord Templeman emphasised in <CASEREF><SOC>Rhone v. Stephens</SOC></CASEREF> was that a successor in title to the original covenantor did not incur a liability to perform a positive covenant such as the covenant to repair in that case unless it had some real relation to a right granted in his favour under the conveyance which he did wish to exercise. The reference in his speech to the exercise of those rights being conditional upon the performance of the positive obligation is not, as he made clear, limited to cases in which it is expressly so conditional. (para 27)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>71. The Court of Appeal concluded that the payment of an annual charge to maintain the facilities which the defendants were only entitled to use because of the rights granted by the agreement which contained the positive covenant was relevant to the continued exercise of those rights even though it was not a direct contribution to the cost of their maintenance, (para 28).</P>
<P>72. The Court concluded by stating:
<QUOTE><P>The successors in title (whether under Form A or Form B conveyances) have therefore no answer to these claims unless they can show that the payment covenant has no relation whatever to the Schedule 1 rights which they have continued to exercise. As a matter of construction, that is not correct for the reasons I have given. Although the continued exercise of the Schedule 1 rights is not made expressly conditional upon payment (any more than it was in <CASEREF><SOC>Halsall v. Brizell</SOC></CASEREF> or in <CASEREF><SOC>Thamesmead Town Ltd. v. Allotey</SOC></CASEREF>) the payment is intended to ensure that the rights remain capable of being exercised. <UNDER>The authorities require one to look beyond the express terms of conveyance and consider what in substance the covenantor is paying for. Here, as in</UNDER> <CASEREF><SOC>Hallsal v. Brizell</SOC></CASEREF><UNDER>, the payment, at least in substantial part, is intended to provide a contribution to the cost of maintaining the roads and other facilities over which the owners of the bungalows are granted rights. None of them has ceased to use the roads nor wishes to do so.</UNDER> (Emphasis added) (para 33)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>73. Shortly after the decision in <EM>Wilkinson</EM>, the Court of Appeal of England and Wales issued a decision in <EM>Goodman</EM> which applied the benefit and burden exception.</P>
<P>74. In <EM>Goodman</EM>, the defendants attempted to avoid an obligation to contribute to the maintenance of a road which provided access to their premises. The road was located on the plaintiff's property. An agreement provided the defendant with the right to use the road. The agreement required the plaintiff to maintain the road and the defendants to pay a portion of the expense associated with maintaining the road.</P>
<P>75. The Court of Appeal of England and Wales described the test for the application of the benefit and burden exception as follows:
<QUOTE><P>In <CASEREF><SOC>Davies v. Jones</SOC><CITE>[2009] EWCA Civ 1164</CITE><PAGENUM>at [27]</PAGENUM></CASEREF> the Chancellor, Sir Andrew Morritt, identified from the authorities three conditions which need to be satisfied in order for the burden of a positive covenant such as the one in this case to be enforceable against the covenantor's successors in title. They are, he said:</P>
<P>&ldquo;(1) The benefit and burden must be conferred in or by the same transaction. In the case of benefits and burdens in relation to land it is almost inevitable that the transaction in question will be effected by one or more deeds or other documents.</P>
<P>(2) The receipt or enjoyment of the benefit must be relevant to the imposition of the burden in the sense that the former must be conditional on or reciprocal to the latter. Whether that requirement is satisfied is a question of construction of the deeds or other documents whether the question arises in the case of land or the terms of the transaction, if not reduced to writing, on other cases. In each case it will depend on the express terms of the transaction and any implications to be derived from them.</P>
<P>(3) The person on whom the burden is alleged to have been imposed must have or have had the opportunity of rejecting or disclaiming the benefit, not merely the right to receive the benefit. (para 24)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>76. The Court of Appeal emphasized that the requirement that the benefit must be relevant to the burden was a matter of substance, not form. The Court of Appeal concluded that there was a &ldquo;clear and obvious link between the rights-of-way reserved over Roadway 4 and an obligation to contribute to the cost of repairs.&rdquo; (para 28)</P>
<P>77. According to <EM>Gale on Easements</EM>, it is now &ldquo;settled&rdquo; that the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule has been modified:
<QUOTE><P>It is now settled that that there are two requirements for the enforceability of a positive covenant against a successor in title to the covenantor under this doctrine: first, the condition of discharging the burden must be relevant to the exercise of the rights that enable the benefit to be obtained; secondly, the successor must have the opportunity to choose whether to take or renounce the benefit and thereby escape the burden. So, a successor does not have to contribute to the cost of a facility which he is neither entitled to or chooses not to enjoy.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Gale on Easements</EM> at p. 57</P1></P>
<P>78. As recognized by the trial judge:
<QUOTE><P>To summarize then, the principles espoused in <EM>Rhone</EM>, <EM>Wilkinson</EM> and <EM>Goodman</EM> reflect the current state of the law in England. The <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule continues to apply. However, the burden of a positive covenant will be enforceable against the covenantor's successor-in-title if three conditions are met: the benefit must be conditional on or reciprocal to the burden, and then bearer of the burden must be able to reject or disclaim the benefit, not merely the right to receive it. (para 95)</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>f)</N><TI>The Decision in <EM>Black v. Owen</EM></TI>
<P>79. In <EM>Black</EM>, the Ontario Court of Appeal overturned a decision finding that both the conditional grant principle and benefit and burden principle were part of Ontario law.</P>
<P>80. The decision in <EM>Black</EM> is premised on the lower courts failure to apply the decision in <EM>Amberwood</EM>, which was binding precedent. The parties expressly declined a reconsideration of <EM>Amberwood</EM> by a give judge panel. (para 39)</P>
<P>81. However, the Ontario Court of Appeal did re-affirm the existence of conditional grant principle recognized in <EM>Amberwood</EM>, but found that it did not apply on the facts and was not a &ldquo;separate and distinct exception&rdquo; to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule. (para 63)</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>g)</N><TI>A Measured Modification of the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule is Appropriate</TI>
<P>82. The decision in <EM>Parkinson</EM> requires the Court of Appeal to recognize the benefit and burden principle. If the Court of Appeal is not bound by <EM>Parkinson</EM>, it may modify the common law when it is appropriate to do so.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Rosas v. Toca</SOC><CITE>2018, BCCA 191</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Rosas&rdquo;)</EM></P1></P>
<P>83. In <EM>Rosas</EM>, the B.C. Court of Appeal stated:
<QUOTE><P>Is it open to this Court to modify the law to the extent necessary to give effect to the reasoning in <CASEREF><SOC>Williams v. Roffey Bros</SOC></CASEREF>., NAV Canada and the theses advanced by Professor Waddams, Reiter and others?</P>
<P>In <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Salituro</SOC><CITE>1991 CanLII 17</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1991] 3 S.C.R. 654</CITE><PAGENUM>at 664</PAGENUM></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>, the Court recognized the power of judges to make changes to the common law, where there are sound policy reasons for making the proposed change. While complex changes to the law with uncertain ramifications should be left to the legislature, &ldquo;the courts can and should make incremental changes to the common law to bring legal rules into step with a changing society&rdquo;: Salituro at 666.</P>
<P>While the case here is not Charter litigation, I note the Supreme Court of Canada's direction in <CASEREF><SOC>Canada (Attorney General) v. Bedford</SOC><CITE>2013 SCC 72 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>42</PARANUM></CASEREF>, that a &ldquo;matter may be revisited if new legal issues are raised as a consequence of significant developments in the law&rdquo;: see also <CASEREF><SOC>Carter v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2015 SCC 5 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>44</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Comeau</SOC><CITE>2018 SCC 15 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>29</PARANUM></CASEREF>. In <EM>Carter</EM> the Court wrote:
<QUOTE><P>The doctrine that lower courts must follow the decisions of higher courts is fundamental to our legal system. It provides certainty while permitting the orderly development of the law in incremental steps. However, <EM>stare decisis</EM> is not a straitjacket that condemns the law to stasis. (para 170&ndash;172)</P></QUOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>84. It is appropriate to acknowledge the common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule which are recognized in England and, in part, in Ontario.</P>
<P>85. Reflecting the developments in England, positive covenants should be enforceable against successors in title:
<P1>(a) when the continued enjoyment of the benefit is conditional on the continued performance of the burden; <UNDER>or</UNDER></P1>
<P1>(b) when the burden of the positive covenant is conferred in the same agreement or transaction as the benefit to which it corresponds;</P1>
<P1>(c) when the enjoyment of the benefit is relevant to the imposition of the positive covenant;</P1>
<P1>(d) as long as the successor in title wishes to exercise the right and enjoy the benefit of it, and</P1>
<P1>(e) even if the right is not expressly conditional on the performance of the positive covenant (the benefit and burden principle).</P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>E.</N><TI>The Trial Judge Misinterpreted the Easement Agreement</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>a)</N><TI>Introduction</TI>
<P>86. Although the trial judge purported to construe the Easement Agreement to determine whether the covenant to pay the Parkade Expenses was a condition of the grant of easement, she did not approach the interpretation of the Easement Agreement properly. Particularly the trial judge failed to consider the whole of the Easement Agreement, the surrounding circumstances and its business efficacy. Moreover, the trial judge did not consider whether the Strata Corporation could be required to pay the Parkade expenses pursuant to the benefit and burden principle.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>b)</N><TI>The Failure to Consider the Surrounding Circumstances is an Error of Law</TI>
<P>87. The trial judge's failure to consider the surrounding circumstances in which the Easement Agreement was made is an extricable error of law which permits this court to substitute its own conclusion by properly construing the Easement Agreement by considering the whole of it, the surrounding circumstances and its business efficacy.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Creston Moly Corp. v. Sattva Capital Corp.</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 53</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 53</P1></P>
<P>88. Failing to apply the fundamental rules of contractual interpretation amounts to an error of law. This includes a failure to consider &ldquo;all the surrounding circumstances and not only the words used in documenting the transaction&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Paterson v. Burgess</SOC><CITE>2017 BCCA 298</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>c)</N><TI>Applicable Principles of Contractual Interpretation</TI>
<P>89. The applicable principles are as follows:
<ITEM><P>Contracts are to be interpreted in the &ldquo;factual matrix&rdquo; known to the parties at the time. A written agreement must be understood not in a vacuum, but with &ldquo;knowledge of the genesis of the transaction, the background, the context, the market in which the parties are operating.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hall v. Quicksilver Resources Canada Inc.</SOC><CITE>2015 BCCA 291</CITE><PARANUM>26</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>The words of one provision must not be read in isolation but should be considered in harmony with the rest of the contract and in light of its purposes and commercial context and that meaning must be given to all of the words in a contract
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Tercon Contractors Ltd. v. British Columbia (Minister of Transportation &amp; Highways)</SOC><CITE>2010 SCC 4</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1></P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>The corollary of this principle is that meaning must be given to all of the words in a contract.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Scanlon v. Castlepoint Development Corp.</SOC><YEAR>1992</YEAR><CITE>99 D.L.R. (4th) 153</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1></P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>The interpretation of a contract must recognize commercial or business efficacy and should not result in an absurdity or be unworkable considering the surrounding circumstances.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>1525292 Ontario Ltd. v. Canadian Tire Real Estate Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2004 CanLii 15587</CITE><COURTJUR>ONSC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, para 9</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Staburn Westbank Holdings Ltd. v. Home Depot</SOC><CITE>2015 BCSC 418</CITE><PARANUM>7</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>In determining whether a common law modification to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule applies, the court should consider the substance of the agreement, rather than its form.
<P1><EM>Goodman</EM>, para 28</P1></P></ITEM></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>d)</N><TI>The Easement is Conditional on the Payment of Parkade Expenses</TI>
<P>90. The Easement Agreement grants an easement to use the Parkade but that grant of easement is conditional on the payment of the Parkade Expenses, meaning that the obligation is binding, not as an exception to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule, but because it is part of and limits the scope of the grant of easement.</P>
<P>91. The interrelationship between the first paragraph of section 5.3 of the Easement Agreement and subsections (a) and (b) that follow evidence the conditionality of the grant:
<P1>(a) The first paragraph of section 5 grants the easement &ldquo;...<UNDER>subject to the following terms, conditions and limitations</UNDER>&rdquo;, meaning all of the provisions of section 5.3.</P1>
<P1>(b) Section 5.3 (a) qualifies the extent of the easement granted under section 5.3 by confirming that the area used to access the Parkade may be used by the Residential Strata Owners only the purpose of accessing the Parkade.</P1>
<P1>(c) However, and importantly, there is an almost identical repetition in section 5.3(a) of the subject clause in section 5.3, with the addition of the words &ldquo;herein contained&rdquo;&mdash;the right of the Residential Strata Owners to access the Parkade is &ldquo;<UNDER>subject to the terms, conditions and limitations herein contained</UNDER>&rdquo;. Section 13.6(d) states that the use of the word &ldquo;herein&rdquo; means a reference to the Easement Agreement as a whole and not to any particular section or subsection or other subdivision.</P1>
<P1>(d) The right of the Residential Strata Owners to access (and thereby use) the Parkade is expressly &ldquo;subject to&rdquo; (in other words, conditional on) compliance with and performance of all of the &ldquo;terms, conditions and limitations&rdquo; <UNDER>throughout the whole of the Easement Agreement</UNDER>, which would include being subject to:
<ITEM><P>All of the provisions of section 5.3, including sections 5.3.3 (Reservations and Limitations), 5.3.5 (Covenants), 5.3.6. (Parkade Operating Costs), 5.3.8 (Reimbursement), and 5.3.10 (Requirement to keep accurate operating costs);</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>The &ldquo;condition&rdquo; of &ldquo;Reimbursement&rdquo;, which is explained in sections 5.3.6 and 5.3.7, and specifically provided for in section 5.3.8.</P></ITEM></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>e)</N><TI>This Interpretation is Consistent With Surrounding Circumstances and a Review of the Entire Easement Agreement</TI>
<P>92. This interpretation of the words of the Easement Agreement is consistent with the surrounding circumstances and objective intentions of the parties when the Easement Agreement was made. The parties recognized that it was important for the Residential Strata Owners to be able to use the Parkade, but also to pay for the maintenance and operation of the Parkade. The parties could not reasonably have expected that the Residential Strata Owners would be able to use the Parkade without paying a portion of the costs of maintaining and operating it.</P>
<P>93. The conditional nature of the grant is apparent from a review of the whole of the Easement Agreement.</P>
<P>94. Section 7.1(d) requires that the Appellant Owner operate, maintain and repair the Parkade. But there is an express proviso: &ldquo;...<UNDER>provided the cost sharing provisions of Article 10 shall apply thereto</UNDER>&rdquo;. (Emphasis added) Section 10 refers to Schedule &ldquo;E&rdquo; which provides that the Strata Corporation's share of the Parkade Costs is 80%.</P>
<P>95. The obligation to repair and maintain the Parkade (itself a positive covenant) is directly linked to the obligation on the part of the Strata Corporation to pay its share of the Parkade Expenses.</P>
<P>96. This adds an important consideration in the interpretation of the Easement Agreement. The Residential Strata Owners have an easement to use the Parkade. The Parkade will only be available for use by the Residential Strata Owners if it is maintained and operated by the Appellant. The Appellant has a positive obligation to maintain and operate the Parkade, but that obligation is expressly conditional on the Strata Corporation paying a share of the costs of operating and maintaining the Parkade. This easement to use the Parkade must be conditional on the Residential Parkade Users paying a portion of the cost of maintaining the Parkade so that it remains available for their use.</P>
<P>97. If the Strata Corporation is not required to pay its share of the Parkade Expenses, the Appellant is no longer required to operate, maintain and repair the Parkade, which cannot be consistent with the objective intentions of the parties at the time the Easement Agreement was made. The logical result of this is that if neither party is required to observe their respective positive obligations, the Parkade will cease to operate. That is a result that is surely inconsistent with the objective purposes of the Easement, its commercial context and would create an absurdity.</P>
<P>98. The conditional nature of the Appellants obligation to repair and maintain the parkade is consistent only with the conditional nature of the grant of easement. If the obligation to repair, maintain and operate the Parkade is conditional on payment of a portion of the maintenance expenses, the grant of easement itself must also be conditional on payment of a portion of the expenses because the grant will be worthless if the Parkade is not maintained, repaired or operated by the Appellant.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>f)</N><TI>The Benefit and Burden Principle Applies</TI>
<P>99. If the grant of easement is not conditional on payment of the Parkade Expenses, the Residential Strata Owners are required to pay the Parkade Expenses pursuant to the benefit and burden principle because:
<P1>(a) the benefit (the right to use the Parkade) is conveyed in the same agreement (the Easement Agreement) as the burden (the obligation to pay the Parkade Expenses);</P1>
<P1>(b) the receipt of the benefit is relevant to the imposition of the burden&mdash;the obligation to pay the Parkade Expenses is directly related to the right to use the Parkade; and</P1>
<P1>(c) the Residential Strata Owners are free to decline the right to use the Parkade, in which case they would not have to contribute to the cost of its maintenance.</P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>F.</N><TI>Conclusion</TI>
<P>100. It is time to recognize the common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule that have been recognized by the English courts and, to a lesser extent, the Ontario Courts.</P>
<P>101. On an application of either the conditional grant principle or the benefit and burden principle the Strata Corporation remains obligated to pay the Parkade Expenses pursuant to the Easement Agreement.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="VI">PART 4&mdash;NATURE OF ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>102. The appellant seeks an Order setting aside the decision of the trial judge, dismissing the Petition, declaring that the Strata Corporation remains bound to pay the Parkade Expenses pursuant to the Easement Agreement, requiring the Strata Corporation to pay the costs of the Supreme Court proceeding and of this appeal.</P>
<P>All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
<P>Dated at the City of Vancouver, Province of British Columbia, June 20<SUP>th</SUP>, 2018.</P>
