<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">OPENING STATEMENT</TI>
<P>1. The Appellant, a well-established developer, is seeking to overturn the strong and longstanding authority in Canada against positive covenants being unenforceable against successors in title that has been a fixture of the common law for more than a century. It asks for this drastic change in the law so that it can impose positive covenants for payments on the Respondent, strata corporation which never assumed those obligations.</P>
<P>2. The Appellant asks for this extraordinary change in the law despite the absence of any Canadian precedent. Indeed, Canadian courts have expressed a justified skepticism about the principles that the Appellant seeks to import into our common law.</P>
<P>3. The Appellant also presented no evidence to support the need for such a drastic change. Indeed, the problems the Appellant is having in enforcing the covenants are entirely of its own creation. The Appellant built the development, created the strata corporation, drafted the easement for itself, entered into it with itself and then made no apparent effort to cause the strata corporation to assume it. The Appellant could have provided for the maintenance of the parkade at issue through the existing law and subject to the protections under the <EM>Strata Property Act</EM>, [SBC 1998] c. 43 (&ldquo;SPA&rdquo;). They failed to do so. There is no reasonable basis for this Court to save the Appellant by creating new law for its benefit.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART 1&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P>4. This dispute is over the enforceability and the terms of an airspace parcel easement agreement (&ldquo;the Easement Agreement&rdquo;). The Appellant negotiated the Easement Agreement for itself and executed it with itself before subdividing the development lands to create the Respondent, strata corporation.
<P1>Reasons for Judgement, para. 34 &amp; 44. A.R., p. 26 &amp; 28.</P1></P>
<P>5. There is no dispute that the cost-sharing obligations in the Easement Agreement are &ldquo;positive covenants.&rdquo; The Easement Agreement requires the developer to operate and maintain the parkade, and it requires the strata corporation to pay 80% of those expenses.
<P1>Reasons for Judgement, para. 38 &amp; 58, A.R., p. 27 &amp; 31.</P1></P>
<P>6. The strata corporation considers the expenses to be too high, much higher in fact, than what the developer represented in its disclosures to the original purchasers. The strata corporation sought the declaration that it was not bound by the positive covenants in the easement so that the parties could negotiate a more reasonable funding arrangement.</P>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>The Jameson House Development</TI>
<P>7. Jameson House is an airspace parcel development. It consists of five separate airspace parcels constructed in a single concrete high-rise over top of an underground parkade, located on the remainder lands owned by the Appellant.
<P1>Reasons for Judgement, para. 28, A.R., p. 24.</P1></P>
<P>8. The 138 residential strata lots and common property managed by the strata corporation are located on levels 14 through 37 of the building, in what was formerly described in the materials as &ldquo;Air Space Parcel #1&rdquo; or &ldquo;ASP 1&rdquo;.
<P1>Reasons for Judgement, para. 31, A.R., p. 25.</P1></P>
<P>9. Parking for the development is located within the remainder parcel and is provided via an automated parking and storage system (the &ldquo;APSS&rdquo;) which can accommodate up to 238 vehicles. The APSS is a &ldquo;driverless&rdquo; system. Users drive their cars into an elevator located in the remainder, exit the elevator, and the APSS whisks away the car and parks it. When the user is ready to retrieve her car, she requests it from her unit and descends by elevator to the parking level. If everything goes according to plan, her car will be waiting for her by the time she arrives at the parking level.
<P1>Reasons for Judgement, paras. 31-32, A.R., p. 25-26.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>The Developer's Actions before the Deposit of the Strata Plan</TI>
<P>10. The Appellant's lawyer, Mr. De Vuyst provided insight to the lower court in his affidavit into two alternative models used by developers of &ldquo;mixed-use developments&rdquo; such as Jameson House to manage the sharing of costs. He explained the two models as follows:
<P1>a) The first model involves subdividing the development by way of strata plan under the <EM>Strata Property Act</EM> and in turn creating separate sections (residential and non-residential) under s. 193 of the <EM>Strata Property Act</EM> (&ldquo;SPA&rdquo;);</P1>
<P1>b) The second model involves subdividing the development into blocks of three-dimensional space called &lsquo;air space parcels&rsquo; with those portions of the parent parcel of land not so subdivided appropriately called the &lsquo;remainder parcel&rsquo;.
<P2>Reasons for Judgement, paras. 29-30, A.R., p. 25; Affidavit of De Vuyst A.B., p. 628.</P2></P1></P>
<P>11. Mr. De Vuyst then explains why some developers, including apparently his client, in this case, prefer the second, air space parcel model. He deposed:
<QUOTE><P>9. While separate sections under the SPA do provide some degree of autonomy as between the different users, the fact that all strata lots are within a single strata plan and subject to the authority of the owners enables the one group of users to potentially dominate the other.</P>
<P>10. As such, this separate section model has largely given away to the &ldquo;air space&rdquo; model which provides complete autonomy as between the different users subject, of course, to the terms of the governing agreement known as an &ldquo;air space agreement&rdquo; or &ldquo;ASP agreement.&rdquo; The legal relationship between residential and non-residential strata lots is governed by the SPA while the legal relationship between the mixed-use air space parcels is governed not by statute, but by the terms of the ASP agreement hence underscoring the critical importance of the terms of the ASP agreement.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Reasons for Judgement, para. 30, A.R., p. 25; Affidavit of De Vuyst A.B., p. 628.</P1></P>
<P>12. The Chambers Judge found that the Appellant sought to depart from the legislated model of cost-sharing under the <EM>SPA</EM> and instead opted for the ASP model so it could exert more power and control in the building.
<P1>Reasons for Judgement, para. 169, A.R., p. 65.</P1></P>
<P>13. Before the Appellant subdivided ASP 1 to create the strata corporation, and while it owned all parcels in the development, it entered into the Easement Agreement with itself.
<P1>Reasons for Judgement, para. 34, A.R., p. 26.</P1></P>
<P>14. The relevant terms of the Easement Agreement are set out at paragraphs 35&ndash;46 of the Reasons for Judgement.</P>
<P>15. The strata corporation was never a party to the Easement Agreement, and perhaps most importantly, it has never entered into an assumption agreement as was contemplated under Article 9.2(a)(i) of the Easement Agreement.
<P1>Reasons for Judgement, para. 50, A.R., p. 31.</P1></P>
<P>16. No explanation has ever been given as to why the Appellant never attempted to cause the strata corporation to enter into an assumption agreement, something the Appellant had every opportunity to do before it surrendered control of the strata corporation to the owners if such an agreement was in the best interest of the strata corporation.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART 2&mdash;ISSUES ON APPEAL</TI>
<P>17. In response to Part 2 of the Appellant's factum, the Respondent says that the Chambers Judge was correct in holding that:
<P1>a) the <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM> has no exceptions in Canadian law outside of statute; and</P1>
<P1>b) policy and precedent militate against accepting a common law exception to the <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM>.</P1></P>
<P>18. In specific response to Part 2, paragraph 13(d) of the Appellant's factum, the Chambers Judge considered the purpose and circumstances under which the Easement Agreement was made. Indeed, she held that those very circumstances made this a poor case in which to argue for such a significant change of the common law.
<P1>Reasons for Judgement, paras. 26&ndash;34, 44&ndash;50, 169, A.R., p. 24&ndash;26, 28&ndash;31, 65.</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART 3&mdash;ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI>Standard of Review</TI>
<P>19. There are two questions raised by the Appellant on this appeal. The first is whether, as a matter of law, the exceptions to the <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM> should be recognized. The parties' agree that this first issue is a matter of law and is therefore determined by the standard of correctness.</P>
<P>20. The second question is whether the Chambers Judge misinterpreted the Easement Agreement. The Appellant suggests that the Chambers Judge erred in law by failing to take note of the Easement Agreement's purpose and surrounding circumstances. If that were really the case, then that would be a matter of law, and the standard would be correctness. However, that is clearly not the case.</P>
<P>21. The Chambers Judge took note of the purpose and circumstance of the Easement Agreement's creation. It is clear from her review that the Chambers Judge appreciated the rationale of the Easement Agreement as set out by Mr. De Vuyst in his affidavit and the circumstances in which it was created.
<P1>Reasons for Judgement, paras. 26&ndash;34, 44&ndash;50, 169, A.R., p. 24&ndash;26, 28&ndash;31, 65.</P1></P>
<P>22. Thus, the second issue is one of contractual interpretation which is a question of mixed fact and law for which the Chambers Judge is entittled to deference. In other words, the interpretation of the Easement Agreement by the Chambers Judge should not be disturbed unless the Appellant can demonstrate a palpable and overriding error in her analysis.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Sattva Capital Corp. v. Creston Moly Corp.</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 53</CITE><PARANUM>50</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Heritage Capital Corp v Equitable Trust Co</SOC><CITE>2016 SCC 19</CITE><PARANUM>21&ndash;24</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>D.</N><TI>Positive Covenants are not Enforceable Against Successors In Title</TI>
<P>23. It is well established in Canada that positive covenants do not run with the land. This rule has been referred to as the <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM> in these proceedings which is a reference to <CASEREF><SOC>Austerberry v. Corporation of Oldham</SOC><YEAR>1885</YEAR><CITE>29 Ch. D. 750</CITE></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>24. The Austerberry <EM>Rule</EM> was adopted by the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Parkinson v. Reid</SOC><CITE>[1966] SCR 162</CITE></CASEREF>. In that case, the dominant tenement sought to impose a repair or replacement obligation on the servient tenement concerning a damaged staircase. The court refused to impose such a positive obligation stating:
<QUOTE><P>An obligation on the owner of the servient tenement to perform work on it would be inconsistent with the nature of an easement which as regards the servient owner <UNDER>is always negative</UNDER>, the obligation on him being either to suffer or not to do something. [Emphasis Added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Parkinson v. Reid</SOC><CITE>[1966] S.C.R. 162</CITE><PARANUM>13</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>25. The justification for the <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM> is based on the basic common law principle that a person who is not privy to an agreement cannot be bound by it. That liabilities cannot be assigned without the consent of the party to whom the obligation is owed continues to be recognized and is well entrenched in our common law tradition.</P>
<P>26. This Court has followed the <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM> on multiple occasions. In <CASEREF><SOC>Nordin v. Faridi</SOC></CASEREF>, this Court applied the <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM> to allow an appeal by a servient tenement owner because the trial judge had, in interpreting an easement, imposed an obligation to share the cost of a well system on the servient tenement. The court set aside the trial judge's orders and held:
<QUOTE><P><UNDER>It is an essential characteristic of an easement that it does not place on the owner of the servient tenement any obligation to act.</UNDER> Such an obligation can only be imposed by a positive covenant, the burden of which will not pass with the land. As a result the owner of the servient tenement has no obligation to maintain a right-of-way or, as the law is generally understood, to keep in repair a building in respect of which there is an easement of support.</P>
<P>[...] <UNDER>it is impossible to burden land (as opposed to the landowner) with any positive obligations</UNDER> owed towards the neighbouring land.</P>
<P>[...]to interpret the easement agreement in such a manner as to impose a positive obligation on the servient tenement to provide and maintain a water system would be inconsistent with the jurisprudence regarding the nature of an easement. [Emphasis Added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Nordin v. Faridi</SOC><CITE>[1996] B.C.J. No. 61</CITE><COURTJUR>BC CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, para 34 and 41.</P1></P>
<P>27. This Court later described the <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM> and negative covenants as follows in <EM>Westbank</EM>:
<QUOTE><P>The covenant must be negative in substance and constitute a burden on the covenantor's land analogous to an easement. <UNDER>No personal or affirmative covenant requiring the expenditure of money or the doing of some act can, apart from statute, be made to run with the land</UNDER>. [Emphasis Added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Westbank Holdings Ltd. v. Westgate Shopping Centre Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2001 BCCA 268</CITE><PARANUM>16</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>28. Chief Justice Finch, as he then was, followed <EM>Westbank</EM> in <CASEREF><SOC>Aquadel Golf Course Limited v. Lindell Beach Holiday Resort Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF> In that case, the lower court had held that the obligation to maintain land as a golf course was a negative covenant. The Court of Appeal concluded that the covenant was positive and thus, unenforceable. Chief Justice Finch wrote:
<QUOTE><P>A positive covenant does not run with the land, and its character is not altered by registration as a charge in the Land Title Office.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Aquadel Golf v. Lindell Beach Holiday Resort</SOC><CITE>2009 BCCA 5</CITE><PARANUM>4 &amp; 9</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>29. The Ontario Court of Appeal in <EM>Amberwood</EM> considered whether exceptions should be made to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule and concluded that they should not. Justice Louise Charron, then of the Ontario Court of Appeal, wrote the following for the majority:
<QUOTE><P>The rule that positive covenants do not run with the land has been a settled principle of the English common law for well over a century and it is undisputed that it has clearly been adopted in Canada: <CASEREF><SOC>Parkinson v. Reid</SOC><CITE>1966 CanLII 4</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1966] S.C.R. 162</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>56 D.L.R. (2d) 315</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>. It appears to be equally undisputed that the rule at times causes inconvenience, that its application in some cases may even result in unfairness, and that the present state of the law should be modified to meet the needs of modern conveyancing. However, <UNDER>it is my view that the call for reform is not one for the courts to answer but for the legislature. Any change in the law in this area could have complex and far-reaching effects that cannot be accurately assessed on a case-by-case basis. The need to preserve certainty in commercial and property transactions requires that any meaningful reform be achieved by legislation that can be drafted with careful regard to the consequences</UNDER>. [Emphasis Added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Durham Condominium Corporation No. 123 v. Amberwood Investments Limited</SOC><CITE>2002 CanLII 44913</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>30. This conclusion was recently affirmed by the Ontario Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Black v. Owen</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 397</CITE></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>31. The Supreme Court of Canada very recently in <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> summarized the principles underlying the <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM> as follows:
<QUOTE><P>[25] The idea of a payment obligation running with land is by its nature unusual. In fact, <UNDER>it is undisputed that at common law, positive covenants cannot run with the land</UNDER>. This rule is founded on the principle that at common law, a person cannot be made liable upon a contract unless he or she was party to it. [Citations Omitted; Emphasis Added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Heritage Capital Corp. v. Equitable Trust Co.</SOC><CITE>2016 SCC 19</CITE><PARANUM>25</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>32. The <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM> applies because the Respondent was not a party to the Easement Agreement and never agreed to assume the obligations of the Easement Agreement. Therefore, it is not possible under common law for the positive covenants in the Easement Agreement to be enforceable against the strata corporation or its owners.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>E.</N><TI>Exceptions to the <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM> may only come from statute</TI>
<P>33. The Ontario Court of Appeal, Alberta Court of Appeal and the Supreme Court of Canada have all confirmed that the <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM> applies despite an express intention to the contrary in an agreement. The Supreme Court of Canada held:
<QUOTE><P>The rule against positive covenants running with the land applies even if an agreement contains an express intention to the contrary (<CASEREF><SOC>Amberwood Investments Ltd. v. Durham Condominium Corp. No. 123</SOC><YEAR>2002</YEAR><CITE>2002 CanLII 44913</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>58 O.R. (3d) 481</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>).</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Heritage Capital</EM>, para 25; <CASEREF><SOC>Equitable Trust Company v 604 1st Street S.W. Inc.</SOC><CITE>2014 ABCA 427</CITE><PARANUM>62</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>34. In <EM>Heritage Capital</EM> the court considered <EM>Amberwood</EM> and <EM>Westbank</EM> and emphasized that the only exceptions to the <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM> recognized in law must come from statute:
<QUOTE><P>...the common law rule is that &ldquo;[n]o personal or affirmative covenant, requiring the expenditure of money or the doing of some act, can, <UNDER>apart from statute</UNDER>, be made to run with the land&rdquo; (V. Di Castri, Registration of Title to Land (loose-leaf), vol. 1, at p. 10&ndash;4 (emphasis added), quoted in <CASEREF><SOC>Westbank Holdings Ltd. v. Westgate Shopping Centre Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2001 BCCA 268 (CanLII)</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>155 B.C.A.C. 1</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>, at para. 16).</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Heritage Capital</EM>, para 2.</P1></P>
<P>35. It is important to note the underlining in the passage above from <EM>Heritage Capitol</EM> is original. The Supreme Court emphasized that positive covenants can only run with the land under statute.</P>
<P>36. The Ontario Court of Appeal confirmed this interpretation of <EM>Heritage Capitol</EM> in <CASEREF><SOC>Black v. Owen</SOC></CASEREF>. In that case, the plaintiff sought to enforce positive covenants in a trust deed for the payment of the maintenance of certain lands and roadways. The defendants argued that the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule applied. The lower court ruled in favour of the plaintiff by applying the exceptions to Austerberry that the Appellant in this case wants to apply here. The Court of Appeal granted the appeal, finding that the exceptions would run contrary to the majority in <EM>Amberwood</EM> and <EM>Heritage Capitol</EM>:
<QUOTE><P>The majority decision in <EM>Amberwood</EM> remains good law in Ontario. Recently, in <EM>Heritage Capital</EM>, the Supreme Court cited <EM>Amberwood</EM>, at para. 25, for the proposition that the positive covenants rule applies &ldquo;even if an agreement contains an express intention to the contrary&rdquo;. The Court went on to state: &ldquo;As a result, the common law rule is that &lsquo;[n]o personal or affirmative covenant, requiring the expenditure of money or the doing of some act can, <UNDER>apart from statute</UNDER>, be made to run with the land&rsquo;&rdquo; (emphasis in original; citations omitted).</P>
<P><EM>Amberwood</EM> was directly relevant to the matters in issue before the Appeal Judge. It was also a precedent binding on her. Absent reconsideration by this court of its decision in <EM>Amberwood</EM>, (which is not requested by the parties), or an authoritative pronouncement by the Supreme Court of Canada that displaces the majority's holdings in <EM>Amberwood</EM> (which not only has not occurred, <UNDER>but would run contrary to <EM>Heritage Capital</EM></UNDER>), it was not open to the Appeal Judge to disregard the binding majority opinion in <EM>Amberwood</EM> and, instead, to adopt and follow the minority opinion in that case. She erred in law in so doing. [Emphasis Added]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>37. Paragraph 25 of the reasons from <EM>Heritage Capitol</EM> explains why only statute can create and exception to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule:
<QUOTE><P>[25] The idea of a payment obligation running with land is by its nature unusual. In fact, it is undisputed that at common law, positive covenants cannot run with the land. This rule is founded on the principle that at common law, a person cannot be made liable upon a contract unless he or she was party to it. [Citations Omitted]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>38. That any exceptions to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule should be left to the legislatures is sensible as reform in this area requires extreme caution and should not be approached on a case by case basis.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>F.</N><TI>The Court Should Not Adopt Exceptions to the <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM></TI>
<P>39. The Appellant seeks to reform the common law to accept the conditional grant and the benefit and burden exception. In the alternative, the Appellant seeks recognition and the application of the conditional grant principal recognized in <EM>Amblewood</EM>. This factum will deal with the exceptions first.</P>
<P>40. No court in Canada has ever recognized the exceptions in any binding decision.</P>
<P>41. The Ontario Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Black v. Owen</SOC></CASEREF> confirmed that the exceptions do not form part of the law in Ontario at paragraph 6:
<QUOTE><P>For lengthy reasons it explained, including the uncertainties and many frailties of the existing common law in England in this area of the law, the majority in <UNDER><EM>Amberwood</EM> concluded that it would be inadvisable to adopt the benefit and burden exception</UNDER> to the rule about positive covenants in Ontario. <UNDER>For essentially the same reasons, although perhaps not as explicitly, the majority also declined to import the conditional grant exception</UNDER> as discussed in the English jurisprudence into Ontario law, holding, in any event, that it was not available on the facts to assist the defaulting landowner. [Emphasis Added]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>42. The Ontario Court of Appeal in <EM>Amberwood</EM> rejected the exceptions on the basis that the exceptions were &ldquo;subject to of much debate and criticism&rdquo; in England (paras 66&ndash;72) and because changes to the common law would create &ldquo;unmanageable confusion&rdquo; and therefore, should be left to the legislatures.
<P1><EM>Amberwood</EM>, paras. 75-76.</P1></P>
<P>43. Far from endorsing a condition grant or benefit and burden exception in <EM>obiter</EM>, the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Parkinson et al. v. Reid</SOC><CITE>[1966] SCR 162</CITE></CASEREF> refused to adopt the principle. Instead, the Court dismissed the ground on the basis that even if it assumed the principal existed, it would not apply.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Parkinson et al. v. Reid</SOC><CITE>[1966] SCR 162</CITE></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>44. Before reforming the common law, this Court must also consider the unanimous decision of <EM>Friedmann</EM> in which the Supreme Court of Canada considered the three circumstances when it is appropriate to reform the common law:
<QUOTE><P>[42] Before examining whether the criticisms raised above merit the abolition of the sealed contract rule, it is necessary to understand the principles which govern judicial reform of the common law. In the past, this Court has considered the conditions which must be present to effect a change in the common law in several cases. From these cases, some general principles have emerged. A change in the common law <UNDER>must be necessary to keep the common law in step with the evolution of society, to clarify a legal principle, or to resolve an inconsistency. In addition, the change should be incremental, and its consequences must be capable of assessment.</UNDER></P>
<P>[43] ...On the other hand, courts will not intervene where the proposed change will have complex and far-reaching effects, setting the law on an unknown course whose ramifications cannot be accurately measured: see <EM>Bow Valley</EM>, supra, at para. 93. The rationale for judicial restraint in making changes to the common law was expressed by McLachlin J. (as she then was) in Watkins, supra, as follows, at p. 760:
<QUOTE><P>The court may not be in the best position to assess the deficiencies of the existing law, much less problems which may be associated with the changes it might make. The court has before it a single case; major changes in the law should be predicated on a wider view of how the rule will operate in the broad generality of cases. Moreover, the court may not be in a position to appreciate fully the economic and policy issues underlying the choice it is asked to make. [Citations Omitted; Emphasis Added]</P></QUOTE></P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Friedmann Equity Developments Inc. v. Final Note Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2000] 1 S.C.R. 842</CITE><PARANUM>42-43</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>45. None of the three circumstances for a change of the common law apply in this case. The change is not necessary to clarify a legal principle or to resolve an inconsistency. The <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM> and its limited statutory exceptions are clearly defined in Canada.</P>
<P>46. Concerning the final circumstance regarding societal changes, Justice McLachlin's (as she then was) called for caution at paragraph 46 of <EM>Friedmann</EM>:
<QUOTE><P>[46] While our common law rules must be in step with the evolution of society as a whole, when examining a proposed change to a rule of property or contract law, we must also examine whether the rule is consistent or inconsistent with commercial reality. A rule may have a rationale which appears to be anachronistic while continuing to serve a useful commercial purpose. Our common law is replete with artificial rules which, although they may appear to have no underlying rationale, promote efficiency or security in commercial transactions. Such rules, in the circumstances where they apply, must be followed to create a legally recognized and enforceable right or obligation. Parties, therefore, structure their relations with these rules in mind and the rules themselves become part of commercial reality. Commercial relations may evolve in such a way that a particular rule may become unjust and cumbersome, and may no longer serve its original purpose. When the hardship which a rule causes becomes so acute and <UNDER>widespread</UNDER> that it outweighs any purpose that it may have once served, it is certainly open to a court to make an incremental change in the law. However, <UNDER>there must be evidence of a change in commercial reality which makes such a change in the common law necessary.</UNDER> [Emphasis Added]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>47. A more than century old and well-entrenched principle of property law should not be altered without the ability to consider the broad ramifications it may cause.</P>
<P>48. The Respondents did not offer any evidence to suggest that there has been a widespread change in commercial reality that would justify changing the common law in the way they have proposed, particularly in the strata context.</P>
<P>49. If anything, the opposite is true. The affidavit of Mr. De Vuyst acknowledges that a legislative solution for cost sharing in a multi-use building already exists under the SPA. The Appellant just preferred the ASP model because it wanted to avoid the protections that the SPA provides. As the Chambers Judge noted at paragraph 169 of her Reasons:
<QUOTE><P>The respondent could have used the <EM>SPA's</EM> separate sections model, but chose not to because it did not want the residential strata owners to overwhelm the others owners in a mixed-use building.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>50. The Appellant's aversion to the democratic protections of the SPA does not amount to evidence of commercial necessity.</P>
<P>51. In its 2012 <EM>Report on Restrictive Covenants</EM>, a committee of the British Columbia Law Institute (BCLI) concluded that reform of the law in this area should be approached with caution:
<QUOTE><P>The matter needs to be approached nevertheless with some caution, because positive obligations are often more onerous than negative ones. A covenant not to build more than one dwelling per lot is easily performed, and a purchaser of property subject to the covenants is not exposed to any greater detriment than the vendor who has performed the covenant by not putting a second building on the property. If the covenant is to maintain and repair works or structures on the property, however, a purchaser cannot be certain of what the future cost of compliance will be.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>BCLI Report, p. 29.</P1></P>
<P>52. Like the example given by the BCLI committee, the strata corporation, in this case, has little certainty of what future costs JHV will seek to impose on it for the parkade, other than the fact that JHV will seek 80% of whatever they may be from the Respondent.</P>
<P>53. The BCLI committee concluded that a change to allow positive covenants should be implemented through the enactment of legislation. One concern that the committee expressed was that landowners should not suddenly find themselves liable under positive covenants entered into by their predecessors in title:
<QUOTE><P>... the change would only apply to positive covenants entered into after the enactment of legislation implementing this proposal. In this way, landowners who do not bear any liability now under positive covenants made in the past by their predecessors in title would not become instantly subject to springing liabilities.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>BCLI Report, page x.</P1></P>
<P>54. A sudden reform of the law in this area by the courts on a case by case basis would likely give rise to the &ldquo;springing liabilities&rdquo; that so concerned the BCLI committee. This is a strong reason for the courts to show restraint in this area. Parties subject to real estate transactions in Canada have structured their dealings by the more than 100-year-old <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM>. It would be harsh for land owners to suddenly find that they are subject to positive covenants on title which they never agreed to and never thought would apply to them.</P>
<P>55. The court should be particularly wary of introducing exceptions on a case-by-case basis in the strata context. The SPA already has statutory exceptions to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> rule. These exceptions exist to force the repair of strata property and fund common expenses. For example, strata corporations can collect funds from owners to pay for common expenses (SPA, s. 92) and owners must repair and maintain their strata lots (SPA, Standard Bylaw 2(1)). These obligations that run with the land have been crafted so that they are subject to a democratic system of governance where owners have a say in the expenses and obligations they incur.
<P1><EM>Strata Property Act</EM> [SBC 1998] C.43.</P1></P>
<P>56. Cost sharing agreements with third parties of the kind created by JHV are not contemplated in the SPA. They are also contrary to the usual democratic and accountable way in which common costs are decided and imposed on strata owners.</P>
<P>57. The Appellant was uncomfortable with the owners of Jameson House having a say in, among other things, the management, maintenance, and funding of the parkade under the democratic process of the SPA. Instead, JHV created its own alternative model based on a 231-page adhesion contract in the form of an easement.</P>
<P>58. It is easy to contemplate, how such cost-sharing agreements can be subject to abuse, particularly in BC. Unlike in other jurisdictions, the SPA does not specifically contemplate their use and has no specific protections in place for strata lot purchasers. By contrast, in Ontario, ss. 111&ndash;113 of the <EM>Condominium Act, 1998</EM>, S.O. 1998, c. 19 provides specific protections and remedies regarding contracts concerning the mutual use of shared facilities between condo owners and third parties put in place by the owner developer.</P>
<P>59. One of the objectives of the SPA is consumer protection against developers. The deposit of the strata plan in the Land Title Office brings the strata corporation into existence, but until the first general meeting, the owner developer controls the strata corporation under ss. 5&ndash;8 of the SPA. Before the first conveyance, an owner developer has broader powers than even an elected strata council, including the right to pass resolutions without a general meeting (s. 8). With these expansive powers, it is possible that owner-developers may attempt to bind strata corporations to unfavorable contracts in favour of their own interests, including onerous cost-sharing agreements.</P>
<P>60. Section 6(1) of the SPA is the sole protection for future owners against an owner developer that might seek to ameliorate its own position at the expense of the strata corporation:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>6.</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><TI>Owner developer's standard of care</TI>
<SSECP>In exercising the powers and performing the duties of a council, the owner developer must
<PARA><N>(a)</N><PARAP>act honestly and in good faith with a view to the best interests of the strata corporation, and</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>exercise the care, diligence and skill of a reasonably prudent person in comparable circumstances.</PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>61. If the Appeal is granted, this Court would allow the Appellant and other developers to skirt the protections of s. 6 because the strata corporation's assumption of the positive covenants registered before the creation of the strata corporation would not be required. Unscrupulous developers could do a great deal of mischief to strata lot purchasers if the court paved the way for them to register positive covenants on title that would be excepted from both the <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM> and s. 6 of the SPA.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>G.</N><TI>A Strata Corporation cannot be subject to obligations that run with land</TI>
<P>62. The strata corporation represents the owners in this matter. The individual owners that the strata corporation represents in this matter are not bound by the positive covenants of the Easement Agreement because they never assumed them.</P>
<P>63. The strata corporation itself is not bound for the same reason and because it is incapable of being bound by an obligation that runs with the land.</P>
<P>64. A strata corporation cannot be subject to any obligation that runs with land because the strata corporation does not own any land.</P>
<P>65. Under s. 66 of the <EM>SPA</EM> the individual owners of the strata corporation own all the common property and common assets as tenants in common. The strata corporation merely manages the common property and common assets for the benefit of the owners under ss. 3 and 72 of the SPA.</P>
<P>66. That the owners, not the strata corporation, own all the real property on the strata plan was confirmed by the Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton v. Ball</SOC><CITE>2006 BCCA 243</CITE><PARANUM>3</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>67. The exceptions to the Austerberry Rule advocated by the Appellant would allow a positive covenant to run with land. However, the notion that a strata corporation can be bound by an obligation that runs with land is contrary to the nature of how strata property is owned. Thus, the strata corporation by its very nature cannot be subject to an obligation that is based on the ownership of land.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>H.</N><TI>The Conditional Grant Principle Should Not Be Adopted</TI>
<P>68. The Chambers Judge refused to adopt the conditional grant principle recognized by the Ontario Court of Appeal at paragraphs 85-86 of <EM>Amberwood</EM> but held that even if she did, it would not apply in this case.
<P1>Reasons for Judgement, para. 171&ndash;176. A.R., pp. 66-67.</P1></P>
<P>69. This Court should affirm that decision and refuse to adopt the principle.</P>
<P>70. Adoption of the principle would create uncertainty in the law. Counsel in this case and others have struggled to give examples of where this principle would practically apply or how it is in any way distinguishable from the common law exceptions <EM>Austerberry Rule</EM> that have been rejected by the Courts in Canada.</P>
<P>71. In <CASEREF><SOC>Strata Plan NWS 3457 v Strata Plan LMS 1425</SOC><CITE>2017 BCSC 1346</CITE></CASEREF>, Mr. Justice Branch confessed great difficulty in deriving a principled distinction between the rejected &ldquo;conditional grant exception&rdquo; and the &ldquo;conditional grant principle.&rdquo; He held that:
<QUOTE><P>While the Ontario Court of Appeal has apparently sought to preserve some room for interpreting the grant of a positive easement in a way that sustains it, if the grant is sufficiently tied to the positive condition, <UNDER>I find that the adoption of this approach into B.C. law is not justified, and would introduce too much uncertainty into the law</UNDER>. The struggles that experienced counsel had before me drawing a distinction between the rejection of the conditional grant exception and accepting an exception when the grant is sufficiently conditional, only highlights the uncertainty that would be created if the <EM>Amberwood</EM> exception were adopted as proposed. Plaintiff's counsel conceded that he was not aware of any case where a party had successfully applied the <EM>Amberwood</EM> exception for the benefit of the party owed obligations under a positive grant. This lack of authority makes it even more difficult to accept the proposed exception, given the lack of established principles as to how and when it could be applied. [Emphasis Added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Strata Plan NWS 3457 v Strata Plan LMS 1425</SOC><CITE>2017 BCSC 1346</CITE><PARANUM>41</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>72. Such a confused principle should also not form part of the law in Canada because it would allow parties to create obligations in easements that the courts have repeatedly said are contrary to the very nature of an easement.</P>
<P>73. However, if the Court does adopt the principle, then the Court should affirm the Chambers Judge's interpretation of the easement that the principle does not apply at paragraph 175 of her Reasons for Judgement:
<QUOTE><P>Nowhere does the Easement Agreement provide that the right to use the parkade is conditional upon the acceptance of the burden contained in the positive covenant that contemplates the cost-sharing of expenses to operate the parkade.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>74. This interpretation of the contract by the Chambers Judge is owed deference on appeal and is also correct.</P>
<P>75. The Easement Agreement does not make the grant of parking rights conditional on the continuing payment of the &ldquo;Parkade Charges.&rdquo; The consideration for the grant is expressly stated to be the consideration received from the individual strata lot owners when they purchased their units as per Article 5.3.1.</P>
<P>76. The benefit of the right to park is granted to the &ldquo;Residential Parkade Users&rdquo; which is defined in Article 5.3 of the Easement Agreement as the &ldquo;Air Space Parcel 1 Owner and its Strata Corporation&rdquo;. By contrast &ldquo;individual Strata Unit Owners&rdquo; are the ones that gave consideration for the granting of the Easement Agreement according to Article 5.3.1.</P>
<P>77. According to Article 5.3.7 and 5.3.8, the obligation to pay parkade charges falls on the &ldquo;Residential Parkade Users&rdquo; and not the &ldquo;individual Strata Unit Owners&rdquo;.</P>
<P>78. The grant of the easement was a separate transaction under consideration granted by different parties and is, therefore, independent of the alleged obligation to pay parkade charges.</P>
<P>79. The Respondent also did not assume the obligation to pay 80% of the parkade costs as a part of the transaction described in Article 5.3.1. Under the terms of the easement, the Respondent would be billed by the Remainder owner regardless of whether consideration was received by the &ldquo;individual Strata Unit Owners&rdquo;; the extent of the use of the APSS by the &ldquo;individual Strata Unit Owners&rdquo;; or if the &ldquo;individual Strata Unit Owners&rdquo; ceased using the parkade all together.</P>
<P>80. Even the English exceptions advocated by the Appellant do not apply in those circumstances. As noted by the learned author in <EM>Preston &amp; Newsom's Restrictive</EM> Covenants <EM>(10th Ed.):</EM>
<QUOTE><P>The benefit and burden <UNDER>must be conferred in or by the same transaction</UNDER> and be relevant to one another, <UNDER>and the person on whom the burden is alleged to have been imposed must have, or have had, the opportunity of rejecting or disclaiming the benefit, not merely the right to receive it.</UNDER> [Emphasis Added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Preston &amp; Newsom's Restrictive Covenants (10th Ed.), p. 105.</P1></P>
<P>81. As Justice Charron, as she then was, noted at paragraph 69 of <EM>Amberwood</EM> the House of Lords &ldquo;rejected any notion of a &ldquo;pure principle of benefit and burden&rdquo; that would bind successors to burdens that stood independently of the right.&rdquo;</P>
<P>82. There are no provisions in the easement which would purportedly relieve the strata corporation of its alleged ob ligation to pay for the 80% of the parkade costs even if some or all of the owners ceased to access the parkade. Thus, the burden stands independent of the right and cannot be said to be conditional on each other.</P>
<P>83. The principle described in <EM>Amberwood</EM> can also not be based on general language or vague statements of intent that the Appellants have relied on in their interpretation of the easement. Otherwise, as the Court in <EM>Amberwood</EM> noted:
<QUOTE><P>[87] ...it would be open to anyone to simply abolish the [<EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule] at the stroke of a pen. All that would be required would be a general statement of intent that the continuing right to the use and enjoyment of all the benefits in an agreement was conditional upon the acceptance of the burden contained in any of the covenants. The recognition of such a wide exception would constitute a profound change in the law.</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="VI">PART 4&mdash;ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>84. The Respondent asks that the appeal be dismissed, with costs.</P>
<P>All of which is respectfully submitted,</P>
