<BLOCK3><N>a)</N><TI><UNDER>Introduction</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. The rigid application of the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule can no longer be justified. According to the <EM>Report on Restrictive Covenants</EM> published by the British Columbia Law Institute:
<QUOTE><P>In British Columbia as elsewhere, courts have routinely applied the requirement [that only negative covenants may run with the land] on the basis of previous authority without attempting to justify it. Judicial reluctance to relax the requirement of negativity has been described as &ldquo;a phobic response to entering new terrain&rdquo;... An examination of the merits of allowing positive covenants to run with the land is overdue. (p. 23)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>2. The Appellant does not seek a &ldquo;drastic&rdquo; change to the common law, or to &ldquo;overturn&rdquo; the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule. The Appellant asks the court to recognize common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule that have been applied in England (the historical home of the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule) and, to some extent, in Ontario for many years. The modifications proposed are more consistent with the decision in <EM>Austerberry</EM> than the rigid application of the rule extracted from the decision.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>b)</N><TI><UNDER>The Court Should Not Be Reluctant to Modify the Common Law</UNDER></TI>
<P>3. The Court of Appeal should not be reluctant to make incremental changes to the common law when it is appropriate to do so. The common law is intended to change over time when there are sound policy reasons for the proposed change or to bring legal rules into step with a changing society. The principle of <EM>stare decisis</EM> is not meant to be a &ldquo;straitjacket&rdquo; that prohibits appropriate changes to the common law.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Rosas v. Toca</SOC><CITE>2018 BCCA 191</CITE><PARANUM>171-172</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>c)</N><TI><UNDER>A Change to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule Is Necessary</UNDER></TI>
<P>4. <EM>Friedmann</EM> suggests that a change in the common law may be necessary to keep the common law in step of the evolution of society or to resolve an inconsistency. Any change should be incremental and the consequences of that change should be capable of assessment.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Friedmann and Equity Developments Inc v. Final Note Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2000 SCC 34</CITE><PARANUM>42</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>5. Much has changed since the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule was developed. Land ownership is far more integrated, with people living closer together and sharing facilities and amenities. Most importantly, land registration systems are far more reliable and accessible, which undermines the foundation for the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule. The <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule needs to be modified to keep up with changes to society and commercial realties.</P>
<P>6. The <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule is based on privity of contract. It was intended to protect a purchaser who acquired a property without knowledge of an obligation to pay. That is no longer a realistic risk.</P>
<P>7. In <EM>Stare Decisis and Positive Covenants and Easements: An Inconvenient Straitjacket, The Advocate</EM> Vol. 76, September 2018, Richard Olson explains why the foundation for the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule no longer exists:
<QUOTE><P>If there is such a rule&mdash;and courts today seem to think that there is&mdash;it arose at a time, and in a setting, when title to land and other interests in land arose through deeds. A purchaser might well acquire the fee simple title to the property only to learn later that the title was burdened with an easement or restrictive covenant of which the purchaser had no notice. ...</P>
<P>As to the current circumstances, today, in British Columbia and many other provinces, most interests affecting land are required to be registered in the land title office so that any purchaser has actual notice of them. Why was the land title system adopted? To provide an assurance of title so that a purchaser of land would not be surprised by the appearance of a charge or other interest affecting a parcel of land that might have been missed when a review of the deeds relevant to the purchase was performed. (p.676 - 677)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>8. This case illustrates the vanishing foundation for the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule. Here, the requirement to pay the Parkade Expenses was disclosed to potential purchasers both by registration of the Easement Agreement in the Land Title Registry, and in disclosure statements filed with the Financial Institutions Commission. Potential purchasers were also alerted to the Parkade Expenses because the strata bylaws stated that the strata corporation was bound by the Easement Agreement. No purchaser was at risk of accidentally taking on an unknown obligation.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>d)</N><TI><UNDER>The Five Factors Are Present</UNDER></TI>
<P>9. In <EM>Friedmann</EM>, the Supreme Court of Canada set out five factors that might identify &ldquo;compelling&rdquo; reasons for reform:
<QUOTE><P>These factors were the existence of previous dissenting opinions in this Court, a trend in the provincial appellate courts to depart from the principles adopted in the original decision, criticism of the case or adoption of a contrary rule in other jurisdictions, doctrinal criticism of the case and its foundations, and inconsistency of the case with other decisions. While they are not prerequisites for a change in the common law, these factors help to identify compelling reasons for reform.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Friedmann</EM>, para 43</P1></P>
<P>10. The factors identified in <EM>Friedmann</EM> are present:
<P1>(a) although there are not dissenting opinions of the Supreme Court of Canada (because it has not specifically considered the issue), there was a strong dissent in <EM>Amberwood</EM>;</P1>
<P1>(b) the Ontario Court of Appeal has departed, at least to some extent, from a rigid application of the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule by accepting the conditional grant principle;</P1>
<P1>(c) there has been widespread criticism of the rigid application of the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule in other countries and other countries have adopted common law or statutory exceptions to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule;</P1>
<P1>(d) there is widespread criticism of the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule in Canada, as well as long-standing calls for reforms to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule; and</P1>
<P1>(e) the recent decisions of the Supreme Court of British Columbia are inconsistent with the decisions of the Ontario Court of Appeal in <EM>Amberwood</EM> and <CASEREF><SOC>Black v. Owen</SOC></CASEREF>.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>e)</N><TI><UNDER>There Is No Good Reason to Maintain the Status Quo</UNDER></TI>
<P>11. Given that the foundation for the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule no longer exists, there is no good reason to refuse to modify the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule to relieve its harsh consequences.</P>
<P>12. &ldquo;Fidelity&rdquo; to a common law principle is not a convincing policy reason to maintain that principle:
<QUOTE><P>... It is &ldquo;revolting to have no better reason for a rule of law than that so it was laid down in the time of Henry IV,&rdquo; and &ldquo;still more revolting if the grounds upon which it was laid down have vanished long since, and the rule persists from blind imitation of the past.&rdquo;</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bank of Montreal v. Dynex Petroleum Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2002] 1 S.C.R. 146</CITE><PARANUM>18 -19</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>13. That is especially so when limiting language in the decision in <EM>Austerberry</EM> has been ignored in favour of a rigid and all encompassing rule.
<P1><EM>Olson</EM>, p. 675&ndash;678</P1></P>
<P>14. The arguments of the Respondent do not survive scrutiny:
<P1>(a) it is irrelevant that the Appellant could have developed the property using a strata model, rather than an air space model. Both models have advantages and disadvantages. The choice of model should not be dictated by the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule;</P1>
<P1>(b) the modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule proposed by the Appellant are unlikely to create &ldquo;springing liabilities&rdquo; on people who have organized their affairs in accordance with the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule. The common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule will protect and enforce the reasonable expectations of the parties to an easement. Anyone who organizes their affairs to take advantage of the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule by, for example, acquiring property with the express intention of obtaining the benefit of an easement without the corresponding burden of paying costs associated with it, is unworthy of protection; and</P1>
<P1>(c) there is no credible reason to believe that allowing common law modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule will cause predatory developers to impose unfair cost-sharing agreements on strata owners. Any cost-sharing agreements would have to be disclosed to potential purchasers, which would prevent developers from selling units in a development that had an exploitive cost-sharing regime; and</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>f)</N><TI><UNDER>Conclusion</UNDER></TI>
<P>15. The modifications to the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule proposed by the Appellant are incremental, not &ldquo;drastic&rdquo;. The Appellant does not seek to &ldquo;overturn&rdquo; the <EM>Austerberry</EM> Rule, but rather to modify it in a manner consistent with the decisions of the Ontario Court of Appeal, the English courts and the original decision in <EM>Austerberry</EM>.</P>
<P>16. As Mr. Olson comments:
<QUOTE><P>Under the current view of the law these easements only bind the original parties to the positive obligations (repair, contribution to operating and repair costs and taxes among them) contractually. Subsequent purchasers are not bound and yet are entitled to the benefit of the easement. This seems on any view to be an absurd result, especially since if the agreement had been assumed by the strata corporation, then it would have been enforceable. Why this should be so when the foundation on which the rule in <EM>Austerberry</EM> is based, is so faulty and out of date remains a mystery. Stasis indeed. (p. 678)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
<P>September 21, 2018</P>
<P>&ellip35; Garth McAlister</P>
<P>Counsel to the Appellant</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
